00:34:59.270 --> 00:35:04.580
States strategic bombing survey
for the Pacific theater of war.

00:35:04.580 --> 00:35:08.370
The mission of the survey was
"to measure precisely the impact

00:35:08.370 --> 00:35:11.190
of the bomb, to put
calipers on it instead

00:35:11.190 --> 00:35:13.600
of describing it in
a mode of terms".

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:18.170 position:56%
So as part of the overall report the
team included something called the

00:35:18.170 --> 00:35:19.540
physical damage division.

00:35:19.540 --> 00:35:24.130
It was made up of 150 men including
engineers, ordinance experts,

00:35:24.130 --> 00:35:28.120
interpreters, draftsman and
photographers and it was their job

00:35:28.120 --> 00:35:31.580
to examine the physical effects
of the blast on the chimneys,

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:35.390
walls and reinforced concrete
structures that survived

00:35:35.390 --> 00:35:40.410
and to explain and document the
impact, how the metal and concrete

00:35:40.410 --> 00:35:43.360
and wood reacted to
the intense pressure

00:35:43.360 --> 00:35:46.230
of the heat of the atomic bomb.

00:35:46.230 --> 00:35:50.300
So soon after receiving this email
of the trunk I spent a few days

00:35:50.300 --> 00:35:53.070
in the archives at the New
York Public Library reading

00:35:53.070 --> 00:35:56.330 position:56%
