00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:56.980
Okay, anyone have questions
or comments?

00:45:56.980 --> 00:45:58.280
Yes.

00:45:58.280 --> 00:45:59.580
&gt;&gt; First off where are the book
collections you were talking

00:45:59.580 --> 00:46:01.050
about [inaudible] has his items?

00:46:01.050 --> 00:46:04.410
&gt;&gt; Adam Harrison Levy:
Yes, so great question.

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:07.150
So Bromberg still has
the photographs.

00:46:07.150 --> 00:46:13.680
He wants to put them together
in a book and there's talk

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:17.770
of an exhibition but it's all
very vague and the daughters,

00:46:17.770 --> 00:46:20.460
I mean as you'll know from
-- , daughters are sort of --

00:46:20.460 --> 00:46:23.310
, there's contention in the
family so we'll see what happens.

00:46:23.310 --> 00:46:25.910
I mean it's been at least
five years but they are there,

00:46:25.910 --> 00:46:29.130
they've been digitized, they're
safe and we'll see what happens.

00:46:29.130 --> 00:46:33.780 position:56%
As I said there are hundreds, not
as many as the Hiroshima photographs

00:46:33.780 --> 00:46:35.480
and they are an incredible resource

00:46:35.480 --> 00:46:36.780
so hopefully they'll
see the light of day.

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:39.430
I think they will, it's
just a bit of time.

00:46:39.430 --> 00:46:43.020
The Hiroshima photographs,
a bit of a different story.

00:46:43.020 --> 00:46:47.280 position:56%
After I established the [inaudible]
and I wrote a short article actually

00:46:47.280 --> 00:46:49.470
in The Guardian, ironically
it was the weekend

00:46:49.470 --> 00:46:52.290
that there was the tube bombing
whenever that was, five years ago,

00:46:52.290 --> 00:46:55.290
and so the staff at The Guardian
couldn't make it in and they had

00:46:55.290 --> 00:46:56.930
to shorten the articles,
three people,

00:46:56.930 --> 00:46:59.230
there was like a skeleton
staff and I don't think anyone

00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:02.080
on that day wanted to read
about Hiroshima [laughter],

00:47:02.080 --> 00:47:04.440
so it kind of sunk without
a trace I have to be honest

00:47:04.440 --> 00:47:06.660
but there was a [inaudible]
established

00:47:06.660 --> 00:47:10.590
and there was a circuitous route
but Don Levy was able to sell them,

00:47:10.590 --> 00:47:12.930
I don't know for how much, I
don't think it was a lot of money,

00:47:12.930 --> 00:47:14.950
to the International
Center of Photography

00:47:14.950 --> 00:47:16.860
which now has the photographs.

00:47:16.860 --> 00:47:19.540
They are online and there's an
exhibition that they mounted

00:47:19.540 --> 00:47:22.350
as a result and they
are in the public domain

00:47:22.350 --> 00:47:24.180
because they were taken
by the U.S. military.

00:47:24.180 --> 00:47:26.380
These are the contact
prints not the negatives.

00:47:26.380 --> 00:47:29.400
And the exhibition has never
traveled much to my chagrin.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:31.780
I don't know why because
it's an amazing thing

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:35.660 position:56%
but the ICP itself has changed,
they've just moved locations so it's

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:38.630
in their archive, it's accessible
and hopefully it will see the light

00:47:38.630 --> 00:47:41.000
of day again but it has been
out in the public realm.

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:46.990
Anything else?

00:47:46.990 --> 00:47:48.290
Yes.

00:47:48.290 --> 00:47:52.180
&gt;&gt; So interviewing [inaudible]
so the artist his role was tasked

00:47:52.180 --> 00:47:56.440 position:56%
to document just like all history
is documented, so was it interesting

00:47:56.440 --> 00:48:00.400 position:56%
to interview him because he already
has a certain language already going

00:48:00.400 --> 00:48:05.380
on that you could only beg
for from a regular Joe citizen

00:48:05.380 --> 00:48:07.880
about their experiences?

00:48:07.880 --> 00:48:11.470
So was his interview
different than any others

00:48:11.470 --> 00:48:13.130
or [inaudible], what
was your thoughts?

00:48:13.130 --> 00:48:15.110
&gt;&gt; Adam Harrison Levy: Well he
was definitely the U.S. war artist

00:48:15.110 --> 00:48:16.500
so he didn't interview anyone.

00:48:16.500 --> 00:48:18.930
I mean he hung out with the
troops but he was constantly --

00:48:18.930 --> 00:48:21.180
, I think he was very
burdened by his --

00:48:21.180 --> 00:48:22.920
, I mean you can tell
from his quotes,

00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:24.670
I think he had a breakdown
while he was doing it.

00:48:24.670 --> 00:48:27.780
He just could not square the
reality of trying to capture this

00:48:27.780 --> 00:48:30.690
and this pressure being like Goya,
I mean that he kept coming back

00:48:30.690 --> 00:48:33.830 position:56%
to that but to answer your
question obviously he was an artist.

00:48:33.830 --> 00:48:35.750 position:56%
He was reflective about his process.

00:48:35.750 --> 00:48:39.200
I think he was good at sort of
making links to the common soldier.

00:48:39.200 --> 00:48:42.770
I did interview a lot of
people for the D-Day to Berlin.

00:48:42.770 --> 00:48:45.140
I would say he's probably
more articulate than most

00:48:45.140 --> 00:48:48.230
because he was introspective and he
was an artist and also because of

00:48:48.230 --> 00:48:50.870
that experience, I mean it
forced him to think more deeply

00:48:50.870 --> 00:48:54.260
about his failure to be honest.

00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:57.730
Having said that you
know when veterans

00:48:57.730 --> 00:49:01.130
and I know you've experienced
this, when they feel --

00:49:01.130 --> 00:49:02.440
, you know it's a cliché
but it's true

00:49:02.440 --> 00:49:04.970
and there's a reason why
it's a cliché they won't open

00:49:04.970 --> 00:49:07.810
up to their friends, they
won't open up to their family,

00:49:07.810 --> 00:49:09.690
they will definitely
talk to their colleagues

00:49:09.690 --> 00:49:12.450
and their fellow combatants

00:49:12.450 --> 00:49:16.020
but I also think historians have
an amazing opportunity especially

00:49:16.020 --> 00:49:18.830
at the end of their lives
because they realize they're going

00:49:18.830 --> 00:49:20.930
to pass away and this
is their last chance

00:49:20.930 --> 00:49:25.730
and sometimes the most amazing
things are said and secrets

00:49:25.730 --> 00:49:27.430
that have been kept for
40 or 50 years do come

00:49:27.430 --> 00:49:33.280
out so that's incredibly meaningful
[inaudible] and it's great

00:49:33.280 --> 00:49:37.230
that you're capturing that because
it is -- , you know, what, two,

00:49:37.230 --> 00:49:40.510
three, four years from now
there's not going to be anyone.

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:44.140
[ Inaudible ]

00:49:44.140 --> 00:49:47.130
I think this afternoon is going to
be more about the interview process

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:49.660
and what I go through in terms
of the nuts and bolts of how

00:49:49.660 --> 00:49:53.490
to evoke a question or evoke
answers to ask the questions

00:49:53.490 --> 00:49:59.520 position:56%
that hopefully evoke the answers,
more like a workshop less of a talk.

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:00.850
Yes John?

00:50:00.850 --> 00:50:04.990
&gt;&gt; You talk about evoking
rather than provoking,

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:09.370
how would you compare and
contrast the experience

00:50:09.370 --> 00:50:13.490
of interviewing veterans
with interviewing celebrities

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:14.900
as you've done a bit
of that as well?

00:50:14.900 --> 00:50:16.200
&gt;&gt; Adam Harrison Levy: Yes.

00:50:23.040 --> 00:50:27.510
You know celebrities,
most of them have their --

00:50:27.510 --> 00:50:30.290
, as you'd expect they have
their routine down so kind

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:35.580
of clinically sealed that to the
first question is really important,

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:39.820
like with a veteran you can kind
of start off relatively soft

00:50:39.820 --> 00:50:43.190
and you probably should do because
they haven't been interviewed

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:47.610
but for like a real hardened movie
star I take a lot of time thinking

00:50:47.610 --> 00:50:49.670
of what that first question is
going to be because you want

00:50:49.670 --> 00:50:52.300
to signal this isn't going
to be just any old interview,

00:50:52.300 --> 00:50:54.940
I'm not repping for PR, I'm trying

00:50:54.940 --> 00:50:57.780 position:56%
to get something that's a little bit
different so I spend a lot of time

00:50:57.780 --> 00:50:59.320
on those first questions.

00:50:59.320 --> 00:51:06.030
I think with celebrities
sometimes, I mean this is kind

00:51:06.030 --> 00:51:09.170
of a funny story, it's good
to allow for the tangent.

00:51:09.170 --> 00:51:11.670
Tangents are great in interviews
I mean you get a little nervous

00:51:11.670 --> 00:51:12.970
if you think.

00:51:12.970 --> 00:51:14.270
If you do really great research
you can have the confidence

00:51:14.270 --> 00:51:15.980
that you're going to bring it
back to what I call the spine

00:51:15.980 --> 00:51:18.680
of the interview but if you're
interviewing a celebrity sometimes

00:51:18.680 --> 00:51:20.870
they go on a tangent sort of
to test you so here's a --

00:51:20.870 --> 00:51:22.360
, I don't know why I
think of the story.

00:51:22.360 --> 00:51:29.750
Jeff Daniels, it wasn't BBC, it was
channel 4, it was like 101 films

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:32.860
to see before you die, it was
like a list program and we were

00:51:32.860 --> 00:51:36.710
to interview him about Dumb and
Dumber [laughter] and this is

00:51:36.710 --> 00:51:39.580
like five years after the film came
out and obviously he has ambitions

00:51:39.580 --> 00:51:41.870
to be more than a Dumb or Dumber
actor and he was on Broadway

00:51:41.870 --> 00:51:43.390
and he's gone on obviously.

00:51:43.390 --> 00:51:46.620
He's a really smart, intelligent
actor and he literally was

00:51:46.620 --> 00:51:50.120
in a hotel room, just what you
don't want to do, small hotel room,

00:51:50.120 --> 00:51:51.790
the lights were set up
and literally he came

00:51:51.790 --> 00:51:53.260
down the hallway kind of slumping.

00:51:53.260 --> 00:51:54.560
You could tell he didn't
want to do it.

00:51:54.560 --> 00:51:57.070
He had his publicist kind of
like pulling him by the nose.

00:51:57.070 --> 00:51:58.750
He sat down in the chair

00:51:58.750 --> 00:52:01.500
and I didn't have a great
first question I have to admit

00:52:01.500 --> 00:52:05.330
and I said can you describe
what you did in Dumb and Dumber

00:52:05.330 --> 00:52:06.630
because we are doing this --

00:52:06.630 --> 00:52:10.320
, I mean now this is kind of bold
[laughter], and he kind of looked

00:52:10.320 --> 00:52:13.420
at me like come on buddy I've done
this so many times, forget about it

00:52:13.420 --> 00:52:16.210
and I asked three questions and
I got those sort of no, yes,

00:52:16.210 --> 00:52:20.590
no answers and I knew I was in deep
water and I thought I'm never going

00:52:20.590 --> 00:52:24.060
to be able to use this so why not
just ask him a really tangential

00:52:24.060 --> 00:52:26.320
question and I said
what are your hundred

00:52:26.320 --> 00:52:28.660 position:56%
and one films to see before you die?

00:52:28.660 --> 00:52:29.960
And he kind of lit up.

00:52:29.960 --> 00:52:32.230 position:56%
He's like oh no once really asked me
that before and he started talking

00:52:32.230 --> 00:52:34.730
about Buster Keaton films
and I was sitting there

00:52:34.730 --> 00:52:36.480
and you know I only had
like 20 minutes and I was

00:52:36.480 --> 00:52:39.130
like sweating thinking
where is this going to go

00:52:39.130 --> 00:52:42.160 position:56%
but I thought you know I'll see
where it goes and he started talking

00:52:42.160 --> 00:52:46.620
about Buster Keaton and how he
walks and how buildings fall on him

00:52:46.620 --> 00:52:49.240
and he has this incredible
physical grace and he's going on

00:52:49.240 --> 00:52:51.230
and I see a little twinkle
in his eye and he said yes

00:52:51.230 --> 00:52:53.780
and when I was walking through
the door in this scene in Dumb

00:52:53.780 --> 00:52:56.770
and Dumber I was thinking
about Buster Keaton

00:52:56.770 --> 00:52:58.820
and I thought that's all I need.

00:52:58.820 --> 00:53:01.130
So he did know what he
was doing and so an actor

00:53:01.130 --> 00:53:04.840
or celebrity have the gift
of knowing what you need

00:53:04.840 --> 00:53:06.340
and they can play with
you a little bit.

00:53:06.340 --> 00:53:08.990
A veteran might not necessarily
know what the soundbite is

00:53:08.990 --> 00:53:12.390
but the celebrity, a writer, an
actor will know what you need

00:53:12.390 --> 00:53:15.010
and they will either tease you
with it or they will give it to you

00:53:15.010 --> 00:53:18.250
so that's a big difference.

00:53:18.250 --> 00:53:19.830
Sure, yes?

00:53:19.830 --> 00:53:26.030
&gt;&gt; Were there other war artists
and if so where are their works?

00:53:26.030 --> 00:53:27.330
&gt;&gt; Adam Harrison Levy:
Great question.

00:53:27.330 --> 00:53:28.790
There are more U.S. war artists.

00:53:28.790 --> 00:53:33.500
They did not have the
funding or the support

00:53:33.500 --> 00:53:35.440
that the British war artists had

00:53:35.440 --> 00:53:37.240
and actually Bromberg was
really bitter about that.

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:39.870
They were literally when they
were in London they had bunkbeds

00:53:39.870 --> 00:53:43.090
and no supplies and he
was really pissed off

00:53:43.090 --> 00:53:49.360
because the British counterparts,
Henry Moore, Nash, Sutherland,

00:53:49.360 --> 00:53:52.450
they all had studios and people
would come and visit them

00:53:52.450 --> 00:53:54.590
and they had a whole -- ,
they had the Officers Club

00:53:54.590 --> 00:53:57.700
and they were all taken very
seriously and to Sir Kenneth Clark

00:53:57.700 --> 00:54:01.320
who went on to write Civilization
was in charge of their unit

00:54:01.320 --> 00:54:02.620
so they were very protected.

00:54:02.620 --> 00:54:05.690
In fact Bromberg would go visit
them and he was embarrassed

00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:09.190 position:56%
because he couldn't invite them back
anywhere, there was nowhere to go,

00:54:09.190 --> 00:54:10.920
there was no Officers Club.

00:54:10.920 --> 00:54:13.020
Having said that, and I
haven't done this research,

00:54:13.020 --> 00:54:17.880 position:56%
he said that there was an exhibition
of war art at Westminster Abbey

00:54:17.880 --> 00:54:21.090
and he was there so some of
the American stuff did end

00:54:21.090 --> 00:54:23.820
up in Westminster Abbey
with the British war artists

00:54:23.820 --> 00:54:26.700
but it was definitely not
supported as much as the Brits did

00:54:26.700 --> 00:54:31.050 position:56%
and I think the program still -- ,
I mean you probably know, it goes on

00:54:31.050 --> 00:54:36.510
and I think there were a number
of artists, right, in the Pacific.

00:54:36.510 --> 00:54:39.580
[ Inaudible ]

00:54:39.580 --> 00:54:40.880
I don't, I should.

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:44.350
Do you know their names?

00:54:44.350 --> 00:54:45.650
And I think there was a book.

00:54:45.650 --> 00:54:48.920
It wasn't actually a very good
book but it was a book of their art

00:54:48.920 --> 00:54:51.330
and to be frank it wasn't
as good as the Brits,

00:54:51.330 --> 00:54:53.680
I mean it really wasn't
which is a shame.

00:54:53.680 --> 00:54:55.270
Having said that it
would be interesting

00:54:55.270 --> 00:54:57.500
to find out what survives.

00:54:57.500 --> 00:54:59.880
Who knows maybe some of
them also took photographs.

00:54:59.880 --> 00:55:01.830
I mean he definitely was
issued with that [inaudible]

00:55:01.830 --> 00:55:04.530
and that was a U.S. military
issue which is ironic

00:55:04.530 --> 00:55:07.880
because it's a German camera
[laughter], but go figure.

00:55:07.880 --> 00:55:10.380
I don't know how they
got hold of it.

00:55:10.380 --> 00:55:12.510
All right, thank you so much.

00:55:12.510 --> 00:55:16.830
[ Applause ]

